{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1119"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1119"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.1,0.02,0.06,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29106"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"542"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1454"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with atraumatic lumbar back pain which has progressively been getting worse over the last two days. Over the last week he has felt generally unwell, with fevers and chills. His medical history includes hepatitis C secondary to intravenous drug use. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is pulse 98/min, blood pressure 108/62 mmHg, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. His cardiorespiratory and neurological examinations are normal. There is erythema noted on his lower back with tenderness on palpation over the lumbar region at the level of L2-L4. Track marks are noted in the antecubital fossa. Bloods are taken for Complete Blood Examination, biochemistry and cultures. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HIV serology","Joint aspiration","Urine culture","Echocardiogram","MRI spine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a febrile illness of unknown origin. In the context of intravenous drug use and localised tenderness in the spine, the most suspicious underlying source would be a bacteraemia resulting in osteomyelitis or an epidural abscess. The best investigation for exclusion of an epidural abscess is an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine\u003C/strong\u003E, although a bone scan would be able to provide useful information on the presence of osteomyelitis. At least three sets of blood cultures would be vital in diagnosis, immediately prior to initiating empirical intravenous antibiotic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV serology\u003C/strong\u003E and an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E are important investigations that may be required in the further management of this patient. In particular if a murmur was noted it would be important to exclude infective endocarditis from bacteraemia with an echo. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA urine culture\u003C/strong\u003E can be done as part of a septic screen, however with the suspicion of a epidural abscess the MRI spine is the MOST important next investigation in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA joint aspiration \u003C/strong\u003Eof the spine would not be an appropriate investigation and could potentially spread the infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A suspected epidural abscess needs an urgent MRI spine.","Fever and back pain in an IVDU requires suspicion of an epidural abscess."],"references":["Vakali M, Crum-Cianflone NF. Spinal Epidural Abscess: A Series of 101 Cases.  Am J Med 2017; 130:1458\u201363"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1119"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-07T16:54:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-07T16:54:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":